"{\"continue\":{\"rvcontinue\":\"20151231101000|697572194\",\"continue\":\"||\"},\"warnings\":{\"main\":{\"*\":\"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application.\"},\"revisions\":{\"*\":\"Because \\\"rvslots\\\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used.\"}},\"query\":{\"normalized\":[{\"from\":\"Duncan_D._Hunter\",\"to\":\"Duncan D. Hunter\"}],\"pages\":{\"17910806\":{\"pageid\":17910806,\"ns\":0,\"title\":\"Duncan D. Hunter\",\"revisions\":[{\"timestamp\":\"2015-12-31T10:11:18Z\",\"contentformat\":\"text/x-wiki\",\"contentmodel\":\"wikitext\",\"*\":\"{{for|his father and predecessor|Duncan Hunter}}\\n{{Infobox Congressman\\n| name        = Duncan D. Hunter\\n| image       = Duncan Hunter 113th Congress.jpg\\n| caption     =\\n| state       = [[California]]\\n| district    = {{ushr|California|50|50th}}\\n| term_start  = January 3, 2013\\n| predecessor = [[Brian Bilbray]]\\n| state1      = [[California]]\\n| district1   = {{ushr|California|52|52nd}}\\n| term_start1 = January 3, 2009\\n| term_end1   = January 3, 2013\\n| predecessor1= [[Duncan L. Hunter]]\\n| succeeded1  = [[Scott Peters (politician)|Scott Peters]]\\n| party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\\n| birth_name  = Duncan Duane Hunter\\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1976|12|07}}\\n| birth_place = {{nowrap|[[San Diego]], [[California]], U.S.}}\\n| death_date  =\\n| death_place =\\n| alma_mater  = [[San Diego State University]]\\n| profession  = Politician, military officer, businessman\\n| spouse      = Margaret Hunter<ref name=\\\"OCD201112\\\">{{cite book |title=Official Congressional Directory, 2011\\u20132012: 112th Congress, Convened January 2011 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=fVSkbYQp6qgC&lpg=PA44&ots=dfqP-ybnFj&dq=Granite%20Hills%20Duncan%20Hunter&pg=PA44#v=onepage&q=Granite%20Hills%20Duncan%20Hunter&f=false |accessdate=21 May 2013 |year=2012 |publisher    = Government Printing Office |isbn=9780160886539 |page=44 }}</ref>\\n| children    = 3\\n| religion    = [[Protestantism in the United States|Protestant]]<ref name=\\\"OCD201112\\\"/>\\n| residence   = {{nowrap|[[Lakeside, California|Lakeside]], [[California]], U.S.}}\\n<!--Military service-->\\n|nickname     =\\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States of America}}\\n|branch       = {{nowrap|{{flagicon image|Flag_of_the_United_States_Marine_Corps.svg}} [[United States Marine Corps]]}}\\n|serviceyears = {{nowrap|2001\\u20132005}} (Active Duty)<br>2005\\u2013present (Reserve)\\n|rank         = [[File:US-O4 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Major (United States)#U.S. Army, U.S. Air Force, and U.S. Marine Corps|Major]]<ref name=\\\"MajorUSMCR\\\">{{cite web |url=http://hunter.house.gov/biography |title=Biography |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=Congressman Duncan Hunter |publisher=United States House of Representatives |accessdate=28 April 2013 |quote=Still a marine reservist, he was promoted to captain in 2006, and to major in 2012. }}<br />{{cite news |title=CONGRESS: Temecula part of Hunter\\u2019s district |author=Jeff Horseman |url=http://www.pe.com/local-news/politics/jeff-horseman-headlines/20130222-congress-temecula-part-of-hunters-district.ece |newspaper=[[The Press-Enterprise]] |date=22 February 2013 |accessdate=28 April 2013 |quote=Temecula is home to a number of marines stationed at Camp Pendleton, and Hunter is a major in the Marine Corps Reserve who served two tours in Iraq and another in Afghanistan. }}</ref>\\n|unit         = [[File:1 11unitlogo.jpg|14px]] [[1st Battalion, 11th Marines]]\\n|commands     =\\n|battles      = [[War in Afghanistan (2001\\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]<br />[[Iraq War]]\\n}}\\n'''Duncan Duane Hunter''' (born December 7, 1976) is an American politician and member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] from California who has represented [[San Diego County, California|San Diego County]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]] since 2009. He succeeded his father, [[Duncan Hunter|Duncan L. Hunter]], as the Representative for {{ushr|CA|52}} until 2013. As a result of [[redistricting]], Hunter switched to the neighboring {{ushr|CA|50}}, which he has represented since 2013. His district presently covers almost all of San Diego County except for the coastal and border areas. It includes the cities of [[Escondido, California|Escondido]], [[San Marcos, California|San Marcos]] and [[Santee, California|Santee]] as well as [[Fallbrook, California|Fallbrook]], [[Lakeside, California|Lakeside]] and [[Valley Center, California|Valley Center]] and mountain and desert areas stretching to the [[Imperial County, California|Imperial County]] line.\\n\\nHunter was born in [[San Diego]] and graduated from [[Granite Hills High School (El Cajon, California)|Granite Hills High School]] in [[El Cajon, California|El Cajon]]. He earned a degree in [[Business Administration]] from [[San Diego State University]] and then worked as an information technology business analyst. Hunter resigned the day after the [[September 11 attacks]] and joined the [[United States Marine Corps]]. He attended [[Officer Candidates School (U.S. Marine Corps)|Officer Candidates School]] at [[Marine Corps Base Quantico]] and after graduation, he was commissioned as a second lieutenant. He subsequently served as a [[field artillery]] officer in the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]] after the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and completed a second tour in [[Fallujah, Iraq]], in 2004. During his second tour, he participated in [[Operation Vigilant Resolve]]. In September 2005, Hunter was [[military discharge|honorably discharged]] from active duty but remained in the [[Marine Forces Reserve|Marine Corps Reserve]]. He then started a [[residential development]] company. In 2007, he was recalled to active duty and deployed to [[Afghanistan]] in support of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]. Hunter was honorably discharged from active duty again in December 2007, but continues to serve in the Marine Corps Reserve.\\n\\nOn March 20, 2007, Republican Congressman [[Duncan Hunter|Duncan L. Hunter]] announced that, as part of his [[Duncan Hunter presidential campaign, 2008|2008 presidential campaign]], he would not seek re-election to the House of Representatives in 2008. Duncan D. Hunter announced his candidacy for his father's seat and on June 3, 2008, won the Republican primary to replace his father. He defeated the Democratic nominee, fellow Iraq War veteran [[Michael D. Lumpkin]], in the general election and succeeded his father in Congress. He was the first combat veteran of either Iraq or Afghanistan to serve in the U.S. Congress. As of 2014, he was one of 17 veterans of the Iraq War serving in the U.S. House of Representatives.\\n\\nHunter was re-elected to the seat in 2010. After redistricting following the [[2010 United States Census]], Hunter ran for re-election in the neighboring 50th Congressional district. He was elected to the new seat in 2012 and 2014. In Congress, Hunter has focussed on military, foreign affairs and veterans issues. He serves on the [[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Armed Services]], [[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Education and the Workforce]] and [[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Transportation and Infrastructure]] committees, chairing the [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation|Transportation Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation]].\\n\\n==Early life, education and business career==\\nHunter was born in [[San Diego]], [[California]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/104308/duncan-hunter#.UZsfEqIsnng |title=Representative Duncan D. Hunter's Biography |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |website=Project Vote Smart |publisher=One Common Ground |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref> the son of Helynn Louise \\\"Lynne\\\" (n\\u00e9e Layh) and Duncan Lee Hunter.<ref>{{cite news |title=District attorney happy to do her bit on jury duty |author=Diane Bell |url=http://legacy.utsandiego.com/news/metro/bell/20040219-9999_1m19bell.html |newspaper=San Diego Union Tribune |date=19 February 2013 |accessdate=21 May 2013}}</ref><ref>http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~battle/reps/hunterdd.htm</ref> He graduated from [[Granite Hills High School (El Cajon, California)|Granite Hills High School]] in [[El Cajon, California]]. He attended [[San Diego State University]], where he earned a degree in [[Business Administration]]. Hunter started a web design company in college to help pay for tuition. Upon graduation from San Diego State, he worked full-time in San Diego as an [[information technology]] [[business analyst]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kitto |first=Kris |url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/24151-the-normal-life-of-duncan-d-hunter |title=The 'normal' life of Duncan D. Hunter |publisher=TheHill.com |date=4 March 2009 |accessdate=27 October 2010 }}</ref>\\n\\n==Military service==\\nThe day after the [[September 11 attacks]], Hunter quit his job and joined the [[United States Marine Corps]]. He attended [[Officer Candidates School (U.S. Marine Corps)|Officer Candidates School]] at [[Marine Corps Base Quantico]]. Upon graduation in March 2002, he was commissioned as a second lieutenant. He subsequently served as a [[field artillery]] officer in the [[1st Marine Division (United States)|1st Marine Division]] after the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]] and completed a second tour in [[Fallujah, Iraq]], in 2004, serving in Battery A, [[1st Battalion, 11th Marines]]. During his second tour, he participated in [[Operation Vigilant Resolve]]. In September 2005, Hunter was honorably discharged from active duty but remained in the [[Marine Forces Reserve|Marine Corps Reserve]]. He then started a [[residential development]] company. In 2007, he was recalled to active duty and deployed to [[Afghanistan]] in support of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]; this was his third tour of duty during the [[War on Terrorism]]. Hunter was [[military discharge|honorably discharged]] from active duty in December 2007, but continues to serve  in the [[Marine Corps Reserve]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/news/2009/01/marine_hunter_012409w/|title=Former Marine in Congress vows to help troops|last=Maze|first=Rick|date=24 January 2009|publisher=Marine Corps Times|accessdate=12 February 2011}}<br />{{cite news |title=Battle-tested Marines lead Poway Patriotic Parade |author=Elizabeth Marie Himchak |url=http://www.pomeradonews.com/2011/09/07/battle-tested-marines-to-lead-poway-patriotic-parade/ |newspaper=Pomerado News |date=7 September 2011 |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Hunter was promoted to major in 2012.<ref name=\\\"MajorUSMCR\\\"/>\\n\\nHunter's awards include:<ref>{{cite journal |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |year=2012 |title=MOWW 2012 Distinguished Service Award Recipient |journal=Officer Review |volume=52 |issue=1 |page=14 |publisher=The Military Order of the World Wars |doi= |url=http://www.militaryorder.net/Officer%20Review_July%2012_VOL%2052_1_Web%20Edition%20(3).pdf |accessdate=17 December 2012}}</ref>\\n<center>\\n{|\\n|-\\n| colspan=\\\"3\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=award-star|ribbon=Combat Action Ribbon.svg|width=106}}&nbsp;{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=NavyPres.gif|width=106}}\\n|-\\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=National Defense Service Medal ribbon.svg|width=106}}\\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=1|type=service-star|ribbon=Afghanistan Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=Iraq Campaign ribbon.svg|width=106}}\\n|-\\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary ribbon.svg|width=106}}\\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=0|type=service-star|ribbon=Global War on Terrorism Service ribbon.svg|width=106}}\\n|{{Ribbon devices|number=2|type=service-star|ribbon=Sea Service Deployment Ribbon.svg|width=106}}\\n|} </center>\\n\\n<center>\\n{| class=\\\"wikitable\\\"\\n|-\\n!1st row\\n| colspan=\\\"3\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|[[Combat Action Ribbon]]\\n| colspan=\\\"3\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|[[Presidential Unit Citation (United States)|Navy and Marine Corps Presidential Unit Citation]]\\n|-\\n!2nd row\\n| colspan=\\\"2\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|[[National Defense Service Medal]]\\n| colspan=\\\"2\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|[[Afghanistan Campaign Medal]] w/1 service star\\n| colspan=\\\"2\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|[[Iraq Campaign Medal]] w/2 [[service star]]s\\n|-\\n!3rd row\\n| colspan=\\\"2\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|[[Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal]]\\n| colspan=\\\"2\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|[[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\\n| colspan=\\\"2\\\" style=\\\"text-align:center;\\\"|[[Sea Service Ribbon|Sea Service Deployment Ribbon]] w/ 2 [[service star]]s\\n|}\\n</center>\\n\\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\\n===Elections===\\n====2008====\\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2008#District 52}}\\nOn March 20, 2007, Hunter announced that, as part of his presidential bid, he would not seek re-election to the House of Representatives in 2008.<ref name=\\\"ap032107\\\">{{cite news|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/politics/20070321-1248-ca-hunter-2008.html |title= Duncan Hunter's son looking to replace him in House |author=ASSOCIATED PRESS |date=March 21, 2007 |publisher=San Diego Union-Tribune}}</ref> After his son, Duncan D. Hunter, announced his candidacy for his father's seat, the younger Hunter was recalled by the [[United States Marine Corps]] to serve in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\\u2013present)|Operation Enduring Freedom \\u2013 Afghanistan]]. During Duncan D. Hunter's active service, his wife, Margaret Hunter, campaigned on his behalf. On June 3, 2008 Duncan D. Hunter won the Republican primary with 72% of the vote in a four candidate field and became the Republican nominee to replace his father representing the 52nd District.<ref name=\\\"ap032107\\\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008-statewide-direct-primary/complete-sov.pdf |title=Statement of Vote |author=Debra Bowen  |date=3 June 2008 |work=Secretary of State |publisher=State of California |accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sdcounty.ca.gov/voters/results/primary.xml Primary Election]. Registrar of Voters (June 3, 2008).{{Dead link|date=February 2011}}</ref> In the general election, Hunter defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[Mike Lumpkin]], an Iraq War veteran, 56%\\u201339%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2008-general/sov_complete.pdf |title=Statement of Vote |author=Debra Bowen |date=4 November 2008 |work=Secretary of State |publisher=State of California |accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref><ref name=StarsandStripes_20081106>{{cite news|accessdate=|url=http://www.stripes.com/article.asp?section=104&article=58659|title=Six recent combat veterans win congressional races|first=Leo, III |last=Shane |work= [[Stars and Stripes (newspaper)|Stars and Stripes]]|date=6 November 2008}}</ref> Hunter thus replaced his father, Congressman [[Duncan L. Hunter]] (R-Calif.), who retired from Congress after fourteen terms.<ref name=UnionTribune_20080604>{{cite news |accessdate=|first=Michele |last=Clock|url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/politics/20080604-9999-1n4cong.html|title=Hunter takes GOP primary|work=[[San Diego Union-Tribune]]|date=4 June 2008}}</ref> He was the first combat veteran of either Iraq or Afghanistan to serve in the U.S. Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hunterforcongress.com/bio/ |title=Duncan D. Hunter for Congress |publisher=Hunterforcongress.com |accessdate=27 October 2010}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.politico.com/arena/bio/rep_duncan_d_hunter.html |title=Rep. Duncan D. Hunter |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2012 |work=The Arena |publisher=Politico LLC |accessdate=10 March 2013}}<br />{{cite news |author=Chief Petty Officer Lesley Maceyak |title=News: US Rep. Duncan Hunter Jr. tours Navy Lab, awards GWOT medals |url=http://www.dvidshub.net/news/94605/us-rep-duncan-hunter-jr-tours-navy-lab-awards-gwot-medals#.VKw8Y9LF98E |newspaper=Space and Naval Warfare Systems Command |location=San Diego |date=12 September 2012 |accessdate=6 January 2015 }}<br />{{cite news |author=B.J. Coleman |title=Congressman Duncan D. Hunter squares off against challenger James Kimber in debate sponsored by Veterans Campaign |url=http://www.thealpinesun.com/article/congressman-duncan-d-hunter-squares-against-challenger-james-kimber-debate-sponsored-veteran |newspaper=The Alpine Sun |date=4 October 2014 |accessdate=6 January 2014 }}</ref> As of 2014, he was one of 17 veterans of the Iraq War serving in the U.S. House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.defenseone.com/politics/2014/06/D1-otoole-iraq-war-veterans-congress-mostly-urge-caution/86704/|title=Iraq War Veterans In Congress Mostly Urge Caution|last=O'Toole|first=Molly|date=June 18, 2014|work=Defense One|accessdate=5 January 2015}}</ref>\\n\\n====2010====\\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2010#District 52}}\\nHe won re-election to a second term with 63% of the vote, defeating Ray Lutz and Michael Benoit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-primary/pdf/2012-complete-sov.pdf |title=Statement of Vote |author=Debra Bowen |date=6 January 2011|work=California Secretary of State |publisher=State of California |accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\\n\\n====2012====\\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2012#District 50}}\\nAfter redistricting, Hunter decided to run in the newly redrawn [[California's 50th congressional district]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Walker, Mark |url=http://www.nctimes.com/news/local/sdcounty/article_b78544d7-463f-5501-8ec6-a7de447b33f8.html |title=REGION: Saldana is against Bilbray as redistricting completed |work=U-T San Diego |date=2011-08-16 |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref> In the five-candidate open primary field, Hunter ranked first with 67% of the vote; Democratic nominee David Secor ranked second with 17% of the vote, qualifying for the November election.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-primary/pdf/2012-complete-sov.pdf |title=Statement of Vote |author=Debra Bowen |date=5 June 2012 |work=California Secretary of State |publisher=State of California |accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref> In the general election, Hunter defeated Secor 68%\\u201332%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.ca.gov/elections/sov/2012-general/sov-complete.pdf |title=Statement of Vote |author=Debra Bowen |date=6 November 2012 |work=California Secretary of State |publisher=State of California |accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\\n\\n====2014====\\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in California, 2014#District 50}}\\nIn the primary election, Hunter finished first with 62,371 votes (70%) to Democrat James H. Kimber's 21,552 (24%). In the general election, Hunter defeated Kimber by 111,997 votes (71%) to 45,302 (29%).\\n\\n===Tenure===\\nIn a 2009 interview with [[KPBS-FM|KPBS]], Hunter expressed support for \\\"overriding\\\" the designation of smelt fish as an [[endangered species]], saying that overriding it would reduce unemployment in California.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rep. Duncan D. Hunter Discusses First Year in Office, Economy, Health Care |author=Hank Cook |author2=Doug Myrland |url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2009/jun/11/rep-duncan-d-hunter-discusses-first-year-office-ec/ |newspaper=KPBS |date=11 June 2009 |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> Hunter also opposed the [[Health Care and Education Reconciliation Act of 2010]], saying that it would \\\"take away\\\" the doctor-patient relationship and the right for people to choose \\\"what type of operations they have,\\\" and that it would allow a \\\"government bureaucrat\\\" to make health care decisions for people. In the KPBS interview, Hunter said, \\\"Things that you have problems with now would be exacerbated if you had government-run healthcare.\\\"<ref name=kpbs61109 />\\n\\nAt an April 2010 [[Tea Party movement]] rally in [[Ramona, California]], Hunter advocated for the deportation of United States citizens who are the children of illegal immigrants.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2010/04/lawmaker-from-calif-wants-to-deport-children-of-illegal-immigrants/1 | work=USA Today | title=Calif. congressman wants to deport children of illegal immigrants | date=28 April 2010}}</ref>  At the rally, Hunter said, \\\"It's a complex issue and...you could look and say, 'You're a mean guy. That's a mean thing to do. That's not a humanitarian thing to do.' \\\" Hunter added, \\\"We simply cannot afford what we're doing right now. We just can't afford it. California's going under.\\\" Hunter confirmed the comments to San Diego County's [[North County Times]], telling the newspaper that he also supported House Resolution 1868, a measure that called for the elimination of [[birthright citizenship in the United States]]. Hunter has also expressed support for the controversial [[Arizona immigration law (2010)|2010 Arizona immigration law]], calling it a national security issue and \\\"a fantastic starting point.\\\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox5sandiego.com/news/kswb-hunter-calls-for-deportation,0,1239838.story|title=Congressman's call to deport children of illegals sparks firestorm|last=Ponting|first=Bob|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Fox 5 San Diego|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref>\\n\\nIn July 2010, Hunter introduced legislation into the [[111th Congress]] to allow [[Tobacco in the United States|tobacco]] products to be shipped to service members serving in Iraq and Afghanistan;<ref>{{cite news |title=Hunter seeks loophole to let troops get smokes |author=Rick Maze |url=http://marinecorpstimes.com/news/2010/08/military_mail_tobacco_080210w/ |newspaper=Marine Corps Times |date=2 August 2010 |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref> the legislation died after being referred to committee.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/111th-congress/house-bill/6037 |title=H.R.6037 \\u2013 To amend title 18, United States Code, to provide for an exception to the prohibition against mailing tobacco products for products mailed to members of the Armed Forces serving in a combat zone. |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |work=United States Legislative Information |publisher=Library of Congress |accessdate=10 March 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nHunter opposed the repeal of [[Don't Ask, Don't Tell]], and advocated for delaying the repeal after it was ratified by U.S. President [[Barack Obama]]. In 2011, Hunter introduced legislation to require that all \\\"four military service chiefs certify that the repeal of Don't Ask Don't Tell won't negatively affect their combat units.\\\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2011/jan/21/sd-congressman-challenges-dont-ask-dont-tell-repea/|title=SD Congressman Challenges Don\\u2019t Ask Don\\u2019t Tell Repeal|last=PENNER|first=GLORIA|date=21 January 2011|publisher=KPBS|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref>\\n\\nIn 2011, Hunter voted for the [[National Defense Authorization Act for Fiscal Year 2012]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Connor |last=Sheets |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/ndaa-bill-how-did-your-congress-member-vote-384362 |title=NDAA Bill: How Did Your Congress Member Vote? |publisher=International Business Times |date=2011-12-16 |accessdate=2013-12-06}}</ref>\\n\\nColumnist Dan Murtaugh of the ''[[Press-Register]]'' has suggested that Hunter's 2011 call to rebid the [[littoral combat ship]] program is an attempt to get federal funds for a shipyard in his district.<ref>Murtaugh, Dan. [http://blog.al.com/press-register-business/2011/07/congressman_asks_for_lcs_progr.html \\\"Congressman asks for LCS program review, possible rebidding.\\\"] ''Press-Register'', 7 July 2011.</ref> Hunter returned to the LCS program in 2012, with a call to reduce LCS builds in favor of amphibious ships, because he had read a report that the Marines had leased a ferry with similar characteristics to the LCS and JHSV.<ref>Robbins, Gary. [http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/sep/14/hunter-says-navy-may-need-fewer-littoral-combat-sh/ \\\"Hunter: Navy may need fewer littoral combat ships.\\\"] ''San Diego Union-Tribune'', 14 September 2012.</ref> In 2013 Hunter said the [[United States Navy]] was overworked and spread thin, and said that a \\\"306-ship target might represent the absolute minimum capacity the navy needs\\\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Hunter Opposes Plan for Smaller Navy Fleet |author=Jeanette Steele |url=http://m.utsandiego.com/news/2013/feb/06/tp-hunter-opposes-plan-for-smaller-navy-fleet/ |newspaper=San Diego Union Tribune |date=6 February 2013 |accessdate=7 February 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nHunter has called for the system of awarding the [[Medal of Honor]] to be evaluated, due to the cases of Sergeant [[Rafael Peralta]] and Captain [[William D. Swenson]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Defense too stingy with Medal of Honor, says Duncan Hunter |author=Charles Hoskinson |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/65789.html |newspaper=Politico |date=12 October 2011 |accessdate=18 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Congressman: Medal of Honor system broken |author=Stephen Dinan |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2012/aug/13/congressman-medal-honor-system-broken/ |newspaper=Washington Times |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=The changing process of awarding military's highest medal: Peralta case an example of modern methods interfering with witness accounts, vets say |author=John Wilkens |url=http://m.utsandiego.com/news/2012/dec/23/changing-process-of-awarding-highest-medal/ |newspaper=San Diego Union Tribune |date=23 December 2012 |accessdate=25 January 2013}}</ref>  Even after Secretary of Defense [[Chuck Hagel]] became the third Secretary to deny the award to Peralta, Hunter maintained his pressure on the Pentagon.  In late March 2014, he sent a letter asking the Pentagon to reevaluate Peralta's case, as well as the case of [[Bradley Kasal]], who used his body to shield a fellow Marine from a grenade blast in Iraq in 2004.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.militarytimes.com/article/20140325/NEWS/303250074/Lawmaker-Grant-all-Marines-who-cover-grenades-Medal-Honor| title=Lawmaker: Grant all Marines who cover grenades the Medal of Honor}}</ref>\\n\\nIn 2011, Hunter opposed a complete withdrawal of American forces from Afghanistan, citing the concern of an \\\"unreliable Afghan leadership,\\\" and called upon the Obama Administration to \\\"stop echoing a misshapen worldview that puts American interests last.\\\"<ref>{{cite news |title=How to handle Afghanistan |author=Duncan D. Hunter |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0611/56116.html |newspaper=Politico |date=3 June 2011 |accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref> In October 2012, Hunter returned from a visit to Afghanistan, as part of a [[congressional delegation]], with a more upbeat assessment, stating \\\"Frankly I was very skeptical last year when I went last, and have been, on whether [the Afghans] can do this, but they are.\\\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Hunter reports progress in Afghan war effort |author=Gretel C. Kovach |url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2012/oct/20/hunter-reports-progress-in-afghan-war-effort/ |newspaper=San Diego Union Tribune |date=20 October 2013 |accessdate=26 January 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nIn 2013, Hunter accused the nation's military leaders of theatrics in the cuts that resulted from the failure of Congress to come to a deal to avert sequestration. He listed targeted spending reductions that he would prefer to make instead of the across the board cuts.<ref>{{cite news |title=Pentagon aims ax to make a point with sequester cuts, uses worst-case scenarios to force deal |author=Rowan Scarborough |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/feb/17/pentagon-aims-ax-to-make-a-point-with-cuts-worst-c/?page=all#pagebreak |newspaper=Washington Times |date=17 February 2013 |accessdate=12 February 2013 |quote=As for alternatives to postponing ship deployments, Mr. Hunter suggests cutting a Navy pet project\\u2014its Green Fleet\\u2014and stop funding the Army\\u2019s $28 billion battlefield intelligence processor, which has flunked operational tests. }}</ref> Hunter also voiced his concern regarding potentially different standards for women and men for the same direct combat positions, following the Obama Administration's decision to allow women to serve in those positions.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hunter fears lax standards for women in combat |author=Rick Maze |url=http://www.armytimes.com/mobile/news/2013/03/military-lawmaker-hunter-fears-lax-standards-for-women-in-combat-030813w |newspaper=Army Times |date=8 March 2013 |accessdate=12 March 2013}}<br />{{cite news |title=CONGRESS: Hunter has qualms about women in combat |author=Jeff Horseman |url=http://www.pe.com/local-news/politics/jeff-horseman-headlines/20130222-congress-hunter-has-qualms-about-women-in-combat.ece |newspaper=[[The Press-Enterprise]] |date=22 February 2013 |accessdate=6 March 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nOn July 24, 2013, Hunter voted against the Amash amendment to rein in the domestic surveillance conducted by the NSA.<ref>{{cite news |title=Amash amendment: the full roll call|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2013/jul/25/amash-amendment-full-roll-call|work=The Guardian|date=24 July 2013|accessdate=24 July 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nIn October 2013 Hunter was the only Representative from San Diego County to vote against the bill which ended the nation's 16-day [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|partial government shutdown]], explaining that he voted against it because it did not reduce spending or the national debt.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2013/oct/17/hunter-congress-vote-budget/|title=Duncan Hunter explains 'no' vote on shutdown bill; Alpine Republican was county congressional delegation's only vote against deal|last=Walker|first=Mark|date=October 17, 2013|work=San Diego Union Tribune|accessdate=5 November 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nOn December 4, 2013, Hunter commented that if war with [[Iran]] becomes inevitable, which he \\\"sure as hell\\\" hoped wouldn't happen, the American response should be a \\\"massive aerial bombing campaign\\\" including \\\"[[Tactical nuclear weapon|tactical nuclear devices]]\\\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://freebeacon.com/hunter-if-you-hit-iran-do-it-with-tactical-nuclear-devices/|title=Hunter: If You Hit Iran, Do It With Tactical Nuclear Devices|date=December 4, 2013|work=Washington Free Beacon|accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref> He also said that the culture of Middle Easterners made them unreliable negotiating partners.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20131204/DEFREG02/312040017/Rep-Hunter-US-Should-Use-Tactical-Nukes-Iran-Strikes-Become-Necessary?odyssey=mod_sectionstories |title=Rep. Hunter: US Should Use Tactical Nukes on Iran if Strikes Become Necessary |last1=Bennett |first1=John T. |date=4 December 2013 |website=defensenews.com |publisher=Gannett Government Media Corporation |accessdate=4 December 2013}}</ref>\\n\\nHunter has strongly criticized the Army's use of its internally developed [[DCGS-A]] system for tracking battlefield intelligence. He says that an alternative technology developed by [[Palantir Technologies]] is more effective at identifying [[improvised explosive devices|IEDs]] and is preferred by Army personnel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2014/04/22/congressman-battles-army-officials-over-why-soldiers-dont-have-bomb-predicting-software/|title=\\u2018Matter of Life and Limb\\u2019: The Congressman Who\\u2019s Going to Battle With the Army Over a Software Program|last=Carter|first=Sara|date=April 22, 2014|work=The Blaze|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref> Hunter says that if Lt. Gen. [[Mary A. Legere]] is nominated to head the [[Defense Intelligence Agency]], he will oppose her because of her support of the DCGS-A system.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/205041-hunter-opposes-possible-nominee-to-lead-pentagon-spy-agency|title=Rep. Hunter opposes possible nominee to lead Pentagon spy agency|last=Matishak|first=Martin|date=May 2, 2014|work=The Hill|accessdate=14 May 2014}}</ref>\\n\\nHunter has moved to block a plan by the military to [[Smoking in the United States military|ban sales of tobacco products on bases and ships]], indicating that he believes servicemembers should be able to make their own choices regarding use of tobacco.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.navytimes.com/article/20140507/NEWS05/305070077/Lawmakers-move-block-Navy-plan-restrict-tobacco-sales |title=Lawmakers move to block Navy plan to restrict tobacco sales |last1=Shane III |first1=Leo |date=7 May 2014 |website=www.navytimes.com |publisher=Gannett |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\\n\\nIn 2013 Hunter called for the United States to train and arm Syrian rebels and stated his opinion that President Obama would be breaking the law if he bombed Syria without a Congressional mandate, and that it should be considered an impeachable offense.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.pe.com/articles/-734934--.html |title=SYRIA: Duncan Hunter visits border, urges arming opposition group |last1=Horseman |first1=Jeff |date=August 27, 2013 |website=www.pe.com |publisher=The Press-Enterprise |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2013/sep/3/hunter-obama-inviting-impeachment-strikes-syria/ |title=Hunter: Obama inviting impeachment if he strikes Syria without Congress |last1=Dinan |first1=Stephen |date=September 3, 2013 |website=www.washingtontimes.com |publisher=The Washington Times |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref> In September 2014 Hunter voted against a proposal to train and arm Syrian rebels fighting against Islamic State extremists; he said the proposal didn't go far enough.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://timesofsandiego.com/politics/2014/09/17/duncan-hunter-votes-obamas-syria-request/ |title=Rep. Hunter Is Lone S.D. Vote Against Obama\\u2019s Syria Request |last1=Jennewein |first1=Chris |date=September 17, 2014 |website=timesofsandiego.com |publisher=Times of San Diego LLC |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\\n\\n===Legislation===\\nHunter introduced the [[Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation Act of 2014 (H.R. 4005; 113th Congress)]] into the House on February 6, 2014.<ref name=4005sum>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4005 \\u2013 Summary|url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th-congress/house-bill/4005|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> The bill would amend laws that govern the activities of the [[United States Coast Guard]] (USCG), the [[United States Maritime Administration|Maritime Administration]] (MARAD) within the [[United States Department of Transportation|Department of Transportation]], and the [[Federal Maritime Commission]] (FMC).<ref name=4005cbo>{{cite web|title=H.R. 4005 \\u2013 CBO|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45168|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=1 April 2014}}</ref> Hunter argued that the bill \\\"improves the effectiveness of Coast Guard missions by reducing inefficient operations and enhancing oversight, places the Coast Guard's major systems acquisition program on a sustainable track, and encourages job growth in the U.S. maritime industry by cutting regulatory burdens on job creation.\\\"<ref name=TransportPR>{{cite web|title=Committee Leaders Introduce Coast Guard & Maritime Transportation Bill|url=https://transportation.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=369179|publisher=House Transportation Committee|accessdate=1 April 2014|author=Jim Billimoria|author2=Justin Harclerode|date=6 February 2014}}</ref>\\n\\nA provision in the bill would increase the amount of food aid that must be transported on private U.S.-flagged cargo ships to 75%.  Supporters of the provision argue that it will support jobs in the maritime industry and enhance military readiness by ensuring a viable supply of cargo ships during wars and other emergencies.  Opponents argue that it will increase the cost of food aid and delay delivery by months.  They also argue that most private cargo ships are not \\\"militarily useful\\\".<ref>{{cite news |title=White House Warns Bill Would Crimp Foreign Food Aid |url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303834304579522032756706514 |author=Kristina Peterson |accessdate=May 6, 2014 |publisher=WSJ |date=April 24, 2014}}</ref>\\n\\n===Committee assignments===\\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Armed Services|Committee on Armed Services]]'''\\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities|Subcommittee on Emerging Threats and Capabilities]]\\n** [[United States House Armed Services Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces|Subcommittee on Seapower and Projection Forces]]\\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Education and the Workforce|Committee on Education and the Workforce]]'''\\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education|Subcommittee on Early Childhood, Elementary and Secondary Education]]\\n** [[United States House Education Subcommittee on Workforce Protections|Subcommittee on Workforce Protections]]\\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation|Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation]] (Chairman)\\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\\n\\n==Personal life==\\nHunter, his wife Margaret, and their three children have lived in [[Lakeside, California]] since 2007; he has previously lived in [[Oklahoma]], [[Virginia]] and [[Idaho]].<ref name=kpbs61109>{{cite web|url=http://www.kpbs.org/news/2009/jun/11/rep-duncan-d-hunter-discusses-first-year-office-ec/|title=Rep. Duncan D. Hunter Discusses First Year in Office, Economy, Health Care|last=Crook|first=Hank|author2=Doug Myrland|date=11 June 2009|publisher=KPBS|accessdate=12 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=TheHill_20070320>{{cite news| url=http://thehill.com/leading-the-news/rep.-duncan-hunter-will-not-seek-reelection-2007-03-20.html| title=Congressman Duncan Hunter will not seek reelection| first=Betsy |last=Rothstein | date= 20 March 2007|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]}}</ref>\\n\\n==References==\\n{{Reflist|2}}\\n\\n==External links==\\n{{commons category}}\\n* [http://www.hunter.house.gov Congressman Duncan Hunter] official U.S. House site\\n* [http://www.hunterforcongress.com/ Duncan Hunter for Congress]\\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/California/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Darrell_Issa_%5BR-49%5D}}\\n* {{CongLinks | congbio = H001048 | ballot = Duncan_Hunter | nndb = 090/000038973 | votesmart = 104308 | govtrack = 412283 | opencong = 412283 | rollcall = 28668 | politifact = duncan-hunter | fec = H8CA52052 | opensecrets = N00029258 | assets = duncan-hunter | legistorm = 938/Rep_Duncan_D_Hunter.html | followthemoney = | ontheissues = CA/Duncan_Hunter_Jr_.htm | congress = duncan-hunter/1909 | worldcat = lccn-n2004-64467 | cspan = 1032398 | imdb = 1943385 | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQAFspUAP }}\\n* {{C-SPAN|duncandhunter}}\\n* [http://www.sourcewatch.org/index.php?title=Duncan_D._Hunter Profile] at [[SourceWatch]]\\n\\n{{S-start}}\\n{{S-par|us-hs}}\\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\\n| state=California\\n| district=52\\n| before=[[Duncan Hunter|Duncan L. Hunter]]\\n| after=[[Scott Peters (politician)|Scott Peters]]\\n| years=2009\\u20132013}}\\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\\n| state=California\\n| district=50\\n| before=[[Brian Bilbray]]\\n| start=2013}}\\n{{s-prec|usa}}\\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Himes]]<br /><small>D-[[Connecticut]]}}\\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=203rd}}\\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lynn Jenkins]]<br /><small>R-[[Kansas]]}}\\n{{S-end}}\\n\\n{{CA-FedRep}}\\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\\n\\n{{Persondata <!-- Metadata: see [[Wikipedia:Persondata]]. -->\\n| NAME              =Hunter, Duncan D.\\n| ALTERNATIVE NAMES =\\n| SHORT DESCRIPTION = Recipient of the Purple Heart medal\\n| DATE OF BIRTH     =December 7, 1976\\n| PLACE OF BIRTH    =[[San Diego]], [[California]]\\n| DATE OF DEATH     =\\n| PLACE OF DEATH    =\\n}}\\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunter, Duncan D.}}\\n[[Category:1976 births]]\\n[[Category:Living people]]\\n[[Category:Politicians from San Diego, California]]\\n[[Category:Baptists from the United States]]\\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from California]]\\n[[Category:American military personnel of the Iraq War]]\\n[[Category:American military personnel of the War in Afghanistan (2001\\u2013present)]]\\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps officers]]\\n[[Category:United States Marine Corps reservists]]\\n[[Category:San Diego State University alumni]]\\n[[Category:Recipients of the Purple Heart medal]]\\n[[Category:People from El Cajon, California]]\\n[[Category:Republican Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\"}]}}}}"